 imaging—range from England's surveys of Scotland following the defeat of the 1746 Jacobite rebellion and early twentieth-century photographic mapping of Iraq to images taken in the immediate aftermath of 9/11. Throughout, Kaplan foregrounds aerial imagery's importance to modern visual culture and its ability to enforce colonial power, demonstrating both the destructive force and the potential for political connection that come with viewing from above.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAerial photographyxHistory. 0aPhotographic surveyingxHistory. 0aPhotography, Military. 0aWar photographyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082237008640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372219/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles